tBranch, err := GetCurrentBranch(ctx)\\nif err == nil && currentBranch == branchName {\\n    return resumeFromCurrentBranch(ctx, branchName, force)\\n}\\n```\\n→ Skips checkout, proceeds directly to session restoration\\n\\n**Scenario B: Local branch exists** (lines 71-121)\\n- Checks `BranchExistsLocally(branchName)`\\n- Verifies no uncommitted changes with `HasUncommittedChanges()`\\n- Calls `CheckoutBranch(branchName)` using git CLI (not go-git, see note below)\\n\\n**Scenario C: Remote branch only** (lines 76-101)\\n- Calls `BranchExistsOnRemote(branchName)` to check origin\\n- Prompts user: \\\"Fetch from origin?\\\"\\n- If yes: calls `FetchAndCheckoutRemoteBranch(branchName)`\\n\\n> **Security Note:** Uses git CLI instead of go-git v5 because go-git has a bug that deletes `.entire/` directories during checkout (see CLAUDE.md)\\n\\n#### **Step 3: Checkpoint Discovery** (`resumeFromCurrentBranch`, lines 124-180)\\nOnce on the target branch:\\n\\n**3a. Find checkpoint in commit history** (lines 131-134)\\n```go\\nresult, err := findBranchCheckpoints(repo, branchName)\\n```\\n\\nThis is where **squash merge support** matters. The result contains:\\n```go\\ntype branchCheckpointResult struct {\\n    checkpointIDs     []id.CheckpointID  // MULTIPLE checkpoints (squash merge)\\n    commitHash        string\\n    commitMessage     string\\n    newerCommitsExist bool               // true if newer commits lack checkpoints\\n    newerCommitCount  int\\n}\\n```\\n\\n**3b. Handle missing checkpoints** (lines 135-138)\\n- If no checkpoints found: print \\\"No Entire checkpoint found...\\\" and return\\n- Continue only if `len(result.checkpointIDs) > 0`\\n\\n**3c. Prompt for older checkpoints** (lines 142-155)\\n- If newer commits exist WITHOUT checkpoints (merge commits don't count)\\n- User is prompted: \\\"Resume from this older checkpoint?\\\"\\n- Can be bypassed with `--force` flag\\n\\n**3d. Multiple checkpoints (squash merge)** (lines 157-160)\\n```go\\nif len(result.checkpointIDs) > 1 {\\n    return resumeMultipleCheckpoints(ctx, repo, result.checkpointIDs, force)\\n}\\n```\\n\\n#### **Step 4a: Single Checkpoint Path** (lines 163-180)\\nThe original (and most common) flow:\\n\\n```go\\ncheckpointID := result.checkpointIDs[0]\\n\\n// Lookup metadata from entire/checkpoints/v1 branch\\nmetadataTree, err := strategy.GetMetadataBranchTree(repo)\\nmetadata, err := strategy.ReadCheckpointMetadata(metadataTree, checkpointID.Path())\\n\\nreturn resumeSession(ctx, metadata.SessionID, checkpointID, force)\\n```\\n\\n#### **Step 4b: Multiple Checkpoints Path (Squash Merge)** (`resumeMultipleCheckpoints`, lines 182-255)\\n\\nThis NEW function handles squash merge commits with multiple trailers:\\n\\n1. **Get metadata tree** (lines 189-209)\\n   - Try local `entire/checkpoints/v1` first\\n   - Fallback to remote if not available locally\\n   - Best-effort: if no metadata available, print message and return\\n\\n2. **Sort checkpoints by age** (lines 211-213)\\n   - Critical for squash merges: GitHub squash commits list trailers in **reverse chronological order** (newest first)\\n   - Function `collectCheckpointsByAge()` sorts by `CreatedAt` ascending\\n   - Ensures newest checkpoint writes last and \\\"wins\\\" on disk\\n\\n3. **Restore each checkpoint independently** (lines 216-242)\\n   ```go\\n   for _, cp := range checkpoints {\\n       point := strategy.RewindPoint{\\n           IsLogsOnly:   true,\\n           CheckpointID: cp.CheckpointID,\\n           Agent:        cp.Agent,\\n       }\\n       sessions, restoreErr := strat.RestoreLogsOnly(ctx, point, force)\\n   }\\n   ```\\n   - Calls `RestoreLogsOnly()` which writes session files to agent's session directory\\n   - Skips checkpoints whose metadata is missing (best-effort)\\n\\n4. **Deduplicate sessions** (line 241)\\n   - Function `deduplicateSessions()` merges multiple checkpoints' sessions\\n   - When same session ID appears in multiple checkpoints, keeps the one with latest `CreatedAt`\\n   - Handles the case where GitHub combines multiple commits with the same session\\n\\n5. **Display resume commands** (lines 249-254)\\n   - Calls `displayRestoredSessions()` to print per-session resume commands\\n\\n#### **Step 5: Session Restoration** (`resumeSession`, lines 490-560)\\n\\nFor single checkpoints:\\n1. Read checkpoint metadata to get agent type\\n2. Resolve agent from metadata (crucial for multi-agent support)\\n3. Create session directory if needed\\n4. Call `strat.RestoreLogsOnly()` with the checkpoint\\n5. Display restore commands\\n\\n#### **Step 6: Fallback to Remote** (`checkRemoteMetadata`, lines 457-485)\\n\\nIf metadata branch doesn't exist locally:\\n1. Check if it exists on remote (`origin/entire/checkpoints/v1`)\\n2. If found on remote: automatically fetch it\\n3. If not found: print informational message, exit gracefully\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 4. EDGE CASES AND ERROR HANDLING\\n\\n#### **A. Checkpoint Discovery Edge Cases**\\n\\n**No checkpoint found**\\n- Returns nil without error\\n- Prints: \\\"No Entire checkpoint found on branch 'X'\\\"\\n\\n**Older checkpoint (newer commits without checkpoints)**\\n- Distinguishes regular commits from merge commits (only count regular commits)\\n- Prompts user for confirmation unless `--force` is set\\n- Shows: \\\"Found checkpoint in an older commit\\\" + commit hash + first line of message\\n\\n**Multiple checkpoints (squash merge)**\\n- GitHub's squash merge puts trailers in reverse chronological order\\n- `collectCheckpointsByAge()` sorts by `CreatedAt` ascending before restoring\\n- Newest checkpoint always restores last and wins on disk\\n\\n#### **B. Branch Checkout Edge Cases**\\n\\n**Uncommitted changes**\\n- `HasUncommittedChanges()` check prevents losing work\\n- Returns error: \\\"you have uncommitted changes. Please commit or stash them first\\\"\\n\\n**Invalid branch refs**\\n- Rejects refs starting with `-` to prevent git argument injection\\n- Example: `CheckoutBranch(\\\"-