inking\",\"thinking\":\"The user wants to make sure we test both squash merge formats:\\n\\n1. **GitHub squash merge format** - where trailers appear in the commit body interspersed with bullet points\\n2. **`git merge --squash` format** - where git creates a \\\"Squashed commit of the following:\\\" message with the original commit messages nested inside\\n\\nLet me first understand what `git merge --squash` actually produces as a commit message, versus what GitHub produces. Then I'll figure out if the current test covers both or if I need to split it into two subtests.\\n\\n**GitHub squash merge format:**\\n```\\nPR title (#123)\\n\\n* First commit message\\n\\n\\nEntire-Checkpoint: aaa\\n\\n* Second commit message\\nEntire-Checkpoint: bbb\\n```\\n\\n**`git merge --squash` format:**\\nWhen you do `git merge --squash feature && git commit` (without `-m`), git generates a message like:\\n```\\nSquash commit of the following:\\n\\ncommit abc123\\nAuthor: E2E Test <e2e@test.local>\\nDate:   Mon Mar 3 ...\\n\\n    Add blue doc\\n    \\n    Entire-Checkpoint: 33fb587b6fbb\\n\\ncommit def456\\nAuthor: E2E Test <e2e@test.local>\\nDate:   Mon\\n```\\n\\nSo the key difference is that GitHub's format uses bullet points with trailers inline, while `git merge --squash` nests the full commit details under a header. I need to make sure my test handles both message structures correctly.\\n\\nLooking at the regex pattern `Entire-Checkpoint:\\\\s*([0-9a-f]{12})(?:\\\\s|$)`, it should work for the squash format since the indentation doesn't affect the match—the pattern just looks for the trailer text itself, not its position in the line. The regex will capture the checkpoint hash regardless of leading whitespace.\\n\\nFor the E2E test, I could use `git merge --squash` followed by `git commit --no-edit` to apply the auto-generated squash message without needing an interactive editor. So I need to set the `GIT_EDITOR` environment variable to something that won't block, like `true`, wh